%N A391671 Number of different pawn structures on an n X n chessboard.
%C A391671 On an n X n chessboard, a pawn structure is defined as the distribution of at most n white and n black pawns, subject to the constraint that the first and n-th ranks of the board remain free of pawns.
%F A391671 a(n) = Sum_{w=0..n} Sum_{b=0..n} binomial(n*(n-2),w) * binomial(n*(n-2)-w,b).
%F A391671 a(n) ~ exp(2*n-6) * n^(2*n-1) / (2*Pi). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 12 2026
%e A391671 For n = 3. Only row 2 with 3 squares needs to be considered. These squares can be empty (0), or hold a white pawn (w) or a black pawn (b). Structures: 000,00w,00b,0w0,0ww .. bbb. So, there are 3^3 = 27 structures possible.
%t A391671 a[n_]:=Sum[Sum[Binomial[n*(n-2),w]*Binomial[n*(n-2)-w,b],{b,0,n}],{w,0,n}]; Array[a,15,0] (* _Stefano Spezia_, Feb 12 2026 *)
%o A391671 (PARI) a(n) = sum(w=0, n, sum(b=0, n, binomial(n*(n-2), w) * binomial(n*(n-2)-w, b)));
